{"title_page": "Christian Williams", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Christian Williams\n| image              = christian williams.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1943|7|9}}\n| birth_place        = Brooklyn, NY\n| birth_name         = \n| death_date         = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = \n| education          = Rahway (N.J.) High School\n| alma_mater         = [[Norwich University]]\n| occupation         = American journalist, television writer and yachtsman\n| known_for          = Part of Bob Woodward's investigative team, created the TV drama \"Capital News\" and wrote the Ted Turner biography \"Lead, Follow or Get Out of the Way\"\n| ethnicity          = \n| religion           = \n| networth           = \n| spouse             = Tracy Olmstead Williams\n| parents            = \n| children           = \n| family             = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Christian Williams''' is an American journalist, television writer and yachtsman.<ref>{{cite web|title=Williams Solos to Hawaii \u2013 and Back|url=http://www.palisadesnews.com/index.php/2016/04/20/williams-solos-to-hawaii-and-back/ |publisher=Palisades News|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> A former ''[[Washington Post]]'' editor during the Watergate era, he later created two television dramas and is the author of four books including the Ted Turner biography \"Lead, Follow or Get Out of the Way.\"\n\n==Journalism==\nWilliams joined ''The Washington Post'' in 1972 as an assistant editor of the Style Section. When the cast and crew of the Robert Redford movie ''[[All the President's Men (film) | All The President's Men]]'' descended on the newsroom to conduct research for the film, Williams served as the assignment editor on the article about the experience behind the scenes. \"It was the age of cool. And suddenly we were cool,\" Williams said. \"You could put out nine calls on deadline at 4 o'clock in the afternoon and get nine callbacks in a half an hour. People were paying attention.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=All the President's Men: An Oral History|url=http://www.washingtonian.com/2016/04/03/all-the-presidents-men-movie-oral-history/|publisher=Washingtonian Magazine|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was arts editor at the paper from 1976-1980.<ref>{{cite web|title=It's (wash.) Post Time For 'Capital News'|url=http://articles.philly.com/1990-04-09/entertainment/25919161_1_redmond-dunne-equal-justice-newspaper-reporter|publisher=Philadelphia Daily News|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> In 1981, he was nominated for the Pulitzer Prize for a series on Isidore Zimmerman, wrongly imprisoned for 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Imprisonment of Isidore Zimmerman|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1981/06/30/the-imprisonment-of-isidore-zimmerman/094c19ce-85fc-4ad6-87c5-a6a834dbd6aa/|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> In 1984, he joined Bob Woodward's investigative team.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los Angeles Times to Launch 'West' Magazine Feb. 5|url=http://www.latimes.com/la-mediacenter-2006-0112-story.html|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nIn 1986, ABC produced a three-hour movie of the week, ''Under Siege'', written by [[Bob Woodward]], Richard Harwood and Williams based on their terrorism reporting.<ref>{{cite web|title=`Under Siege' gives melodramatic portrayal of domestic terrorism|url= http://www.csmonitor.com/1986/0207/lsiege.html |publisher=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> After Williams and Woodward penned an episode of the NBC crime drama [[Hill Street Blues]], Williams left the Post and moved to Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hill Street Blues: Writing Credits|url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0601666/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_wr#writers |publisher=IMDB|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith [[David Milch]], Williams created ''[[Capital News]]'', an ABC drama based on a morning newspaper in Washington, D.C. Williams also created ''[[Hercules: The Legendary Journeys]]'' which became a worldwide hit in syndication. He was not involved in the production of the series. Williams was co-executive producer of the HBO funeral-home drama \"Six Feet Under\" when the show was nominated for \"Outstanding Drama Series\" in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Six Feet Under: Awards & Nominations|url= http://www.emmys.com/shows/six-feet-under |publisher=Emmys.com|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Producer: Six Feet Under |url= https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0003994/ |publisher=IMDB|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sailing==\nWilliams has twice sailed from California to Hawaii, single-handed. The first voyage of Thelonious, an Ericson 32-3, took 20 days there and 28 days back. At age 74 he repeated the solo round trip of 5,000 miles on Thelonious II, a 1984 Ericson 38, with 17 days outbound and 22 days return.\n\nVideo documentaries of his sailing adventures have more than 5 million views on the YouTube channel \u201cChristian Williams Sailing.\u201d  <ref>{{cite news |last1=Tinoco |first1=Lily |title=Setting Sail |url=https://www.palipost.com/setting-sail/ |accessdate=9 January 2020 |publisher=Palisadian-Post}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nWilliams chronicled the founding of CNN in the 1981 Ted Turner biography \"Lead, Follow or Get Out of the Way.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Sure Thing: How entrepreneurs really succeed|url= http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/01/18/the-sure-thing |publisher=The New Yorker|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> Williams' 2016 book \"Alone Together: Sailing Solo to Hawaii and Beyond\" recounts his solo sail two years earlier to Hawaii and back in his 32-foot sloop \"Thelonious.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Man Films As He Sails Yacht To Hawaii And Back Without A Crew|url=http://sfglobe.com/2015/10/23/man-films-as-he-sails-yacht-to-hawaii-and-back-without-a-crew/ |publisher=The San Francisco Globe|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n\u201cPhilosophy of Sailing: Offshore in Search of the Universe\u201d, published in 2018, attempts to apply techniques of phenomenology and other forms of inquiry to the experience of isolation and solitude.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.british-weekly.com/?p=23743|title=Christian Williams: sailor, ranconteur, YouTube guru\u2026and my friend with the sewing machine \u2013 The British Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\nHis novel, \u201cRarotonga,\u201d (East Wind Press, 2019), explores the attempt of a controversial millionaire to flee family, the IRS and a murder charge in search of paradise alone on his luxury sailing yacht. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Tinoco |first1=Lily |title=Setting Sail |url=https://www.palipost.com/setting-sail/ |accessdate=9 January 2020 |publisher=Palisadian-Post}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Christian}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Christian Williams\n| image              = christian williams.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1943|7|9}}\n| birth_place        = Brooklyn, NY\n| birth_name         = \n| death_date         = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = \n| education          = Rahway (N.J.) High School\n| alma_mater         = [[Norwich University]]\n| occupation         = American journalist, television writer and yachtsman\n| known_for          = Part of Bob Woodward's investigative team, created the TV drama \"Capital News\" and wrote the Ted Turner biography \"Lead, Follow or Get Out of the Way\"\n| ethnicity          = \n| religion           = \n| networth           = \n| spouse             = Tracy Olmstead Williams\n| parents            = \n| children           = \n| family             = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Christian Williams''' is an American journalist, television writer and yachtsman.<ref>{{cite web|title=Williams Solos to Hawaii \u2013 and Back|url=http://www.palisadesnews.com/index.php/2016/04/20/williams-solos-to-hawaii-and-back/ |publisher=Palisades News|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> A former ''[[Washington Post]]'' editor during the Watergate era, he later created two television dramas and is the author of four books including the Ted Turner biography \"Lead, Follow or Get Out of the Way.\"\n\n==Journalism==\nWilliams joined ''The Washington Post'' in 1972 as an assistant editor of the Style Section. When the cast and crew of the Robert Redford movie ''[[All The President's Men]]'' descended on the newsroom to conduct research for the film, Williams served as the assignment editor on the article about the experience behind the scenes. \"It was the age of cool. And suddenly we were cool,\" Williams said. \"You could put out nine calls on deadline at 4 o'clock in the afternoon and get nine callbacks in a half an hour. People were paying attention.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=All the President's Men: An Oral History|url=http://www.washingtonian.com/2016/04/03/all-the-presidents-men-movie-oral-history/|publisher=Washingtonian Magazine|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was arts editor at the paper from 1976-1980.<ref>{{cite web|title=It's (wash.) Post Time For 'Capital News'|url=http://articles.philly.com/1990-04-09/entertainment/25919161_1_redmond-dunne-equal-justice-newspaper-reporter|publisher=Philadelphia Daily News|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> In 1981, he was nominated for the Pulitzer Prize for a series on Isidore Zimmerman, wrongly imprisoned for 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Imprisonment of Isidore Zimmerman|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1981/06/30/the-imprisonment-of-isidore-zimmerman/094c19ce-85fc-4ad6-87c5-a6a834dbd6aa/|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> In 1984, he joined Bob Woodward's investigative team.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los Angeles Times to Launch 'West' Magazine Feb. 5|url=http://www.latimes.com/la-mediacenter-2006-0112-story.html|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nIn 1986, ABC produced a three-hour movie of the week, ''Under Siege'', written by [[Bob Woodward]], Richard Harwood and Williams based on their terrorism reporting.<ref>{{cite web|title=`Under Siege' gives melodramatic portrayal of domestic terrorism|url= http://www.csmonitor.com/1986/0207/lsiege.html |publisher=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> After Williams and Woodward penned an episode of the NBC crime drama [[Hill Street Blues]], Williams left the Post and moved to Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hill Street Blues: Writing Credits|url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0601666/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_wr#writers |publisher=IMDB|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith [[David Milch]], Williams created ''[[Capital News]]'', an ABC drama based on a morning newspaper in Washington, D.C. Williams also created ''[[Hercules: The Legendary Journeys]]'' which became a worldwide hit in syndication. He was not involved in the production of the series. Williams was co-executive producer of the HBO funeral-home drama \"Six Feet Under\" when the show was nominated for \"Outstanding Drama Series\" in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Six Feet Under: Awards & Nominations|url= http://www.emmys.com/shows/six-feet-under |publisher=Emmys.com|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Producer: Six Feet Under |url= https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0003994/ |publisher=IMDB|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sailing==\nWilliams has twice sailed from California to Hawaii, single-handed. The first voyage of Thelonious, an Ericson 32-3, took 20 days there and 28 days back. At age 74 he repeated the solo round trip of 5,000 miles on Thelonious II, a 1984 Ericson 38, with 17 days outbound and 22 days return.\n\nVideo documentaries of his sailing adventures have more than 5 million views on the YouTube channel \u201cChristian Williams Sailing.\u201d  <ref>{{cite news |last1=Tinoco |first1=Lily |title=Setting Sail |url=https://www.palipost.com/setting-sail/ |accessdate=9 January 2020 |publisher=Palisadian-Post}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nWilliams chronicled the founding of CNN in the 1981 Ted Turner biography \"Lead, Follow or Get Out of the Way.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Sure Thing: How entrepreneurs really succeed|url= http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/01/18/the-sure-thing |publisher=The New Yorker|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> Williams' 2016 book \"Alone Together: Sailing Solo to Hawaii and Beyond\" recounts his solo sail two years earlier to Hawaii and back in his 32-foot sloop \"Thelonious.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Man Films As He Sails Yacht To Hawaii And Back Without A Crew|url=http://sfglobe.com/2015/10/23/man-films-as-he-sails-yacht-to-hawaii-and-back-without-a-crew/ |publisher=The San Francisco Globe|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n\u201cPhilosophy of Sailing: Offshore in Search of the Universe\u201d, published in 2018, attempts to apply techniques of phenomenology and other forms of inquiry to the experience of isolation and solitude.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.british-weekly.com/?p=23743|title=Christian Williams: sailor, ranconteur, YouTube guru\u2026and my friend with the sewing machine \u2013 The British Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\nHis novel, \u201cRarotonga,\u201d (East Wind Press, 2019), explores the attempt of a controversial millionaire to flee family, the IRS and a murder charge in search of paradise alone on his luxury sailing yacht. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Tinoco |first1=Lily |title=Setting Sail |url=https://www.palipost.com/setting-sail/ |accessdate=9 January 2020 |publisher=Palisadian-Post}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Christian}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Bathtubwiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJournalism", "url_page": "//en.