|2449|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n| successor = [[Volkswagen Phideon]] (China)\n}}\n\n[[File:Volkswagen W12.jpg|thumb|[[Volkswagen W12 engine|Volkswagen Group W12]] as fitted in the Phaeton W12]]\n[[File:VW_Concept_D_(IAA_1999)_1.jpg|thumb|left|Volkswagen Concept D at IAA 1999 in Frankfurt]]\n\nThe '''Volkswagen Phaeton''' ({{Audio|GT VW-Phaeton.ogg|listen}}) {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|e\u026a|t|\u0259n}} {{respell|FAY|t\u0259n}} (''Typ'' 3D) was a [[full-size car|Full-size]] ([[F-segment]] in Europe) [[luxury car|luxury]] [[sedan (automobile)|sedan/saloon]] manufactured by the German automobile manufacturer [[Volkswagen]], described by Volkswagen as their \"premium class\" vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volkswagen-sachsen.de |title=Volkswagen Sachsen GmbH |publisher=Volkswagen-sachsen.de |date= |accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Glaesernemanufaktur Dresden |url=http://www.glaesernemanufaktur.de/gmd.jsp?dok=&lang=en&docid=&ap= |title=GlaeserneManufaktur.de |publisher=GlaeserneManufaktur.de |accessdate=2010-10-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405044618/http://www.glaesernemanufaktur.de/gmd.jsp?dok=&lang=en&docid=&ap= |archive-date=2010-04-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Introduced at the [[Geneva Motor Show#2002|2002 Geneva Motor Show]], the Phaeton was marketed worldwide. Sales in North America ended in 2006 and global sales ended in 2016.\n\nThe name Phaeton derives from [[Phaethon|Pha\u00ebton]], the son of [[Phoebus]] (or [[Helios]]) in [[Greek mythology]], by way of the [[Phaeton body|phaeton auto body style]] and the [[Phaeton (carriage)|type of horse-drawn carriage]] that preceded it.\n\nProduction ended in March 2016 and an all-electric second generation was slated to be produced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-12-16/volkswagen-to-stop-making-top-end-phaeton-sedan-by-late-march |title=Volkswagen to Stop Making Top-End Phaeton Sedan in March |last=Behrmann |first=Elisabeth |date=16 December 2015 |website=Bloomberg.com |access-date=16 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://autoweek.com/article/vw-diesel-scandal/vw-suspend-phaeton-anticipation-diesel-crisis-pressures|title = VW suspends Phaeton.|date = |accessdate = December 19, 2015|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Starting in April 2017, the ''Gl\u00e4serne Manufaktur'' Dresden assembles the [[VW e-Golf|e-Golf]] instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnn.de/Dresden/Lokales/Scharfer-Start-fuer-den-e-Golf-aus-Dresden |title=Scharfer Start f\u00fcr den e-Golf aus Dresden |accessdate=2017-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==First and Second Generation (2002\u20132006/2007-2008) (GP0/GP1)==\n[[File:04 Volkswagen Phaeton (6827577840).jpg|thumbnail|left|Pre-facelift Volkswagen Phaeton]]\n\n===Development===\nThe Phaeton was conceived by [[Ferdinand Pi\u00ebch]], then chairman of [[Volkswagen Group]].<ref name=topgear2003/> Pi\u00ebch wanted Volkswagen engineers to create a car that would surpass the German prestige market leaders, [[Mercedes-Benz]] and [[BMW]]. The decision to release the Phaeton was, in part, a response to Mercedes' decision to compete directly with Volkswagen in the European marketplace with the low cost [[Mercedes-Benz A-Class#W168|A-Class]].\n\nIt was also intended to support the Volkswagen brand image. Although the [[Volkswagen Group]] already has a direct competitor in the full sized luxury segment, the [[Audi A8]], the Phaeton was intended to be more of a comfort oriented limousine, like the [[Mercedes-Benz S-Class]] and [[Lexus LS]], while the Audi A8 and [[BMW 7 Series]] are more sport oriented.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/car/02q3/volkswagen_phaeton_4motion_w-12-first_drive_review |title=Volkswagen Phaeton 4MOTION W-12 |department= First Drive Review - Auto Reviews |work=Car and Driver |date= |accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/tests/comparison/living-large/page_6_-_living_large_page_6 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217101312/http://www.roadandtrack.com/tests/comparison/living-large/page_6_-_living_large_page_6 |archive-date=2011-02-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nInitial development of the Phaeton, given the internal project code VW611, began with Pi\u00ebch giving his engineers a list of ten parameters the car needed to fulfill. Most of these specifications were not made known to the public, but a number of them were told to automotive reporters.\n\nOne of them was that the Phaeton should be capable of being driven all day at {{convert|300|km/h|0|abbr=on}} with an exterior temperature of {{convert|50|\u00b0C|0}} whilst maintaining the interior temperature at {{convert|22|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=GoAutoMedia |url=http://www.goauto.com.au/mellor/mellor.nsf/story2/8F252B3F3D6B8266CA25770E00001AC5 |title=Volkswagen 2009 Phaeton - Beijing show: VW facelifts Phaeton \u2013 again |work=GoAuto |date=2010-04-23 |accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref> Pi\u00ebch requested this even though the Phaeton's top speed was electronically limited to {{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}}.<ref name=topgear2003>''Top Gear'' Series 2 Episode 10, July 20, 2003</ref> Another requirement was that the car should possess torsional rigidity of 37,000 [[newton metre|N\u00b7m]]/[[degree (angle)|degree]].\n\nAt the [[International Motor Show Germany#1999|1999 International Motor Show Germany]], Volkswagen presented the [[Volkswagen Concept D|Concept D]], which was essentially a [[hatchback]] prototype of the Phaeton, with very similar design, [[V10 TDI]] engine, air suspension and all wheel drive.\n\n===Overview===\nThe Phaeton's platform, the [[Volkswagen Group D platform#D1s|Volkswagen Group D1 platform]], was shared with the [[Bentley Continental GT]] and [[Bentley Continental Flying Spur (2005)|Bentley Continental Flying Spur]]. Certain systems, such as the [[automatic transmission]] and some [[internal combustion engine|engines]], are also shared with the [[Audi A8]].\n\nCompared to the Audi A8L 4.2 litre FSI quattro, the Phaeton is {{Convert|545|lb|0|abbr=on}} heavier but is still competitive with the lighter A8 in most driving tests, due to the Phaeton's increased engine power (335&nbsp;hp versus 330) and a shorter axle ratio (3.65:1 versus 3.32).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/comparisons/2004-volkswagen-phaeton-page-3|title=2004 Audi A8L vs. BMW 745i, Jaguar XJ8, M-B S430, VW Phaeton Comparison Tests - Page 3 |work= Car and Driver|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> However, the weight gives the Phaeton considerably worse acceleration and poorer fuel economy compared to the A8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/luxury/112_0409_luxury_sedan_comparison/viewall.html|title=2004 Audi A8L vs 2004 BMW 745i vs 2004 Jaguar XJ8 Vanden Plas vs 2004 Lexus LS 430 vs 2004 Mercedes-Benz S430 vs 2004 Volkswagen Phaeton V8 Comparison |date=3 September 2004|work=Motor Trend Magazine|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Phaeton had the longest [[wheelbase]] in the Volkswagen passenger car line.\n\n===Features===\nDevelopment of the vehicle led to over one hundred individual patents specific to the Phaeton.{{citation needed|date=March 2012}} Distinctive features include a draftless four zone climate system, and standard [[Torsen]] based [[4motion]] [[four-wheel drive]].\n\nFor high ride comfort, it introduced [[Adaptive Air Suspension]] with [[Continuous Damping Control]] (CDC)-(Skyhook suspension). The same suspension system, with firmer settings, was introduced in the technically similar [[Audi A8#D3|Audi A8]] in November 2002.\n\nFirst Volkswagen with [[radar]] [[adaptive cruise control]]: [[automatic distance regulator]] (ADR).\n\n===Phaeton Lounge (2005)===\nThe Phaeton Lounge was a concept car based on a lengthened version of the Phaeton with seating for four (two pairs of seats facing each other) in the rear compartment. It features a W12 engine, a reinforced chassis, six speed [[Tiptronic]] automatic transmission, individual climate control for each passenger, front and rear wine coolers, a minibar, multi color mood lighting, a cigar humidor, two 17 inch monitors, DVD changer in the trunk, second DVD player in the rear cabin, and a Bluetooth enabled computer with a broadband connection.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2006/08/09/the-worlds-first-4wd-limo-is-a-volkswagen/ |title=The world's first 4WD limo is a Volkswagen |last=Nunez |first=Alex |website=Autoblog |access-date=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe vehicle was unveiled in 2005 Middle East International Motor Show.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2005/12/23/volkswagen-supersizes-the-phaeton/ |title=Volkswagen supersizes the Phaeton |last=Waterman |first=Stuart |website=Autoblog |access-date=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Production===\nThe Phaeton was hand assembled in an eco friendly factory with a glass exterior, the [[Transparent Factory]] ({{lang-de|Gl\u00e4serne Manufaktur}}) in [[Dresden]], Germany. This factory had a capacity of producing 20,000 vehicles a year, and was planned to expand to 35,000 vehicles a year.<ref name=failedexperiment>{{cite news|title=VW Phaeton: A few facts on a failed experiment|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20160404/OEM01/304049975/vw-phaeton:-a-few-facts-on-a-failed-experiment|accessdate=25 April 2016|work=Autonews|date=Apr 4, 2016}}</ref> It also assembled [[Bentley Continental Flying Spur (2005)|Bentley Continental Flying Spur]] vehicles destined for the European market until October 2006, when all assembly of the Bentley products was transferred to [[Crewe]], England.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nThe Phaeton body was fabricated and painted at the Volkswagen works at [[Zwickau]], Germany, and the completed bodies were transported approximately 100&nbsp;km by special road transport vehicles to the main factory. Most Phaeton engines, the W12 being the notable exception, were built at the VW/Porsche/Audi engine plant in [[Gy\u0151r]], Hungary.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n===Reception and sales===\n[[File:VW Phaeton 3.0 TDI 4Motion Tarantellaschwarz Interieur.JPG|thumb|Interior]]\n\nSales of the Phaeton fell far short of expectations. Its biggest market was China, followed by South Korea.<ref>{{cite web | last = Choi | first = Joseph | date = 30 July 2013 | url = http://www.nada.com/b2b/NADAOutlook/UsedCarTruckBlog/tabid/96/entryid/280/The-Volkswagen-Phaeton-to-Attempt-Successful-Rebirth-in-U-S-Market.aspx | title = The Volkswagen Phaeton to Attempt Successful Rebirth in U.S. Market | publisher = [[National Automobile Dealers Association]] | accessdate = 10 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the manufacturer stated the annual capacity of the new Phaeton plant at [[Dresden]] was 20,000; by September 2006 a four year total of 25,000 had been built,<ref>''skript manufaktura'' \u2013 Magazin der Gl\u00e4sernen Manufaktur Dresden, Nr.&nbsp;7, Herbst/Winter 2006, Seite 63</ref> with production running at approximately 6,000 cars annually. The domestic market was the Phaeton's strongest, with 19,314 Phaetons delivered in Germany alone by January 2009. Production decreased to 10,190 cars in 2012 and 5,812 in 2013.<ref>http://www.volkswagenag.com/content/vwcorp/content/de/homepage.bin.html/marginalparsys/textandimage_3/downloadFile/GB%2B2013_d.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703032256/http://www.volkswagenag.com/content/vwcorp/content/de/homepage.bin.html/marginalparsys/textandimage_3/downloadFile/GB%2B2013_d.pdf |date=2014-07-03 }} Gesch\u00e4ftsbericht 2013</ref> In Phaeton's production run that lasted 15 years, 84,253 units were built.<ref name=failedexperiment/>\n\nIn Canada, 93 Phaetons were sold in 2004, and in the first eight months of 2005, only 21 found owners. In the United States market, 1,433 Phaetons were sold in 2004, and 820 were sold in 2005, leading the company to announce that sales in the North American market would end after the 2006 model year. The [[Volkswagen W12 engine|W12 engine]]d models have depreciated significantly, and sell for a small fraction of their original cost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heise.de/autos/Clever-kaufen-und-Geld-sparen-Restwerte-bei-Gebrauchten--/artikel/s/2605/1\n|title=Gebrauchtschn\u00e4ppchen Phaeton|language=de}}</ref>\n\nThe Phaeton debuted at prices comparable to similar offerings from [[Mercedes-Benz]], [[BMW]], [[Lexus]] and the Volkswagen Group's own [[Audi A8]] (which shared its powertrain with the Phaeton). ''Motor Trend'' suggested that the \"VW badge on the hood may not say 'premium' to many auto shoppers\" but they were impressed at how the Phaeton drove.<ref>[http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/luxury/112_0409_luxury_sedan_comparison/viewall.html#ixzz1uPUeaFkx ]</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, Volkswagen reported the possibility of bringing the Phaeton back to the United States in the car's next product cycle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://noir.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109&sid=a.j7FDas6jw8&pos=12 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120715134415/http://noir.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109&sid=a.j7FDas6jw8&pos=12 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-15 |title=Volkswagen May Bring Back Scirocco, Phaeton to U.S. |date=2011-01-28 |publisher=bloomberg.com }}</ref> In Autumn 2013, ''[[The Economist]]'' placed Phaeton into the report on Europe's biggest loss making cars.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/graphicdetail/2013/09/daily-chart-18 |title=Daily Chart. Europe's biggest loss making cars |newspaper=The Economist | date=2013-09-25}}</ref> In October 2014, ''[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear Magazine]]'' placed the Phaeton on its list of \"The worst cars you can buy right now.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topgear.com/uk/photos/The-worst-cars-you-can-buy-right-now-2014-10-09 |title=The Worst Cars You Can Buy Right Now |publisher=[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear]] magazine |date=2014-10-09 |accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Volkswagen released the first update to the Phaeton. Subtle design changes were made by the introduction of chrome fog light covers and cherry red rear lights. The CD-based navigation system was upgraded to a DVD system, and the 3.0 V6 TDI engine had its power increased from 222 to 230bhp.\n\n==Third Generation (2008 Facelift) (GP2)==\nThe vehicle was unveiled in 2007 Geneva Motor Show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2007/03/07/geneva-motor-show-the-new-vw-phaeton/|title=Geneva Motor Show: The new VW Phaeton|author=Dan Roth|work=Autoblog|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nUpdate included new [[Light-emitting diode|LED]] [[daytime running light]]s, as well as a freshened centre console with revamped controls and materials. New [[gasoline direct injection|Fuel Stratified Injection]] (FSI) [[V6 engine|V6]] petrol engine with greater power and fuel efficiency (206&nbsp;kW / 280 PS) which satisfy [[European_emission_standards#Euro5|Euro-5]] emissions standards is also available.\n\nOther changes to the car for 2009 included: three new types of alloy wheels (17, 18 and 19&nbsp;inch), a slightly modified radiator [[grille]], three new exterior colours, the new leather colour, the new wood trims, white switch illumination instead of red, accent and switch trim in the new \"Warm gray\" colour, an upgraded car key, makeup mirror in the rear on the LWB version, dampers optimised for low-friction, [[reinforced carbon-carbon#Similar products|Carbon fibre-reinforced Silicon Carbide]] (C/SiC) [[ceramic composite]] brakes (front) on the Phaeton [[W12 engine|W12]], as well as a [[rearview camera]] ([[Rear Assist]]) and [[blind spot warning system]] [[Side Assist]].\n\n==Third Generation (2010 Facelift) (GP3)==\n[[File:2013 Volkswagen Phaeton V6 4MOTION TDi SWB Automatic 3.0.jpg|thumb|left|Volkswagen Phaeton (second facelift)]]\n[[File:VW Phaeton 3.0 V6 TDI 4MOTION (2. Facelift) \u2013 Heckansicht, 1. April 2012, Essen.jpg|thumb|right|Volkswagen Phaeton (second facelift)]]\nThe vehicle was unveiled in 2010 Beijing International Automotive Exhibition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vwmedia.com.cn/PageNews/NewsDetails_en.aspx?articleID=430|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116014043/http://vwmedia.com.cn/PageNews/NewsDetails_en.aspx?articleID=430|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 January 2013|title=Volkswagen Group Debuts Six Brands in China at Auto Beijing 2010|website=vwmedia.com.cn|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2010/04/23/beijing-2010-2011-volkswagen-phaeton-ups-the-luxe/ |title=Beijing 2010: 2011 Volkswagen Phaeton ups the luxe |last=Korzeniewski |first=Jeremy |website=Autoblog |access-date=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe car for 2011 got a new front fascia to more closely resemble the Volkswagen styling direction first seen on the Golf Mk VI. This included new LED running lights, bi-xenon headlights and a new bumper with LED fog lights. The rear [[LED]] clusters were altered to mimic those found on facelifted Touran, Sharan, the new Touareg and the new Passat.\n\nThe interior benefited from some new technologies, but retained the 2009 MY layout. The Phaeton was offered as a normal wheelbase and long wheelbase models, with five seat layout or an optional four seat interior. In the five seat version, the front seats can be adjusted 12 ways. Standard features include all wheel drive, air suspension, and four zone automatic climate control. A multifunction steering wheel can be ordered in leather or wood leather.\n\n===New technologies===\n*[[Automatic Distance Control]] adaptive cruise control with new Stop&Go function\n*[[Front Assist]] [[collision avoidance system]]\n*[[Dynamic Light Assist]] non-glare [[highbeam]] <ref name=\"volkswagen-media-services1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.volkswagen-media-services.com/medias_publish/ms/content/en/pressemitteilungen/2010/04/22/phaeton_debuts_with.standard.gid-oeffentlichkeit.html|title=Phaeton debuts with new design and new technologies|accessdate=22 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720152841/https://www.volkswagen-media-services.com/medias_publish/ms/content/en/pressemitteilungen/2010/04/22/phaeton_debuts_with.standard.gid-oeffentlichkeit.html|archive-date=20 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*[[Traffic sign recognition]] that can also detect [[overtaking restriction]]s<ref name=\"volkswagen-media-services1\"/>\n*GPS-Navigation with [[Google Earth]]\n*[[3G]] [[Mobile internet]] ([[UMTS]])\n\n===Transmissions===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n|+Petrol engines\n!Model!!Years!!Types\n|-\n|3.6 V6 FSI||2010\u20132015||six speed automatic\n|-\n|4.2 V8||2010\u20132016||six speed automatic\n|-\n|6.0 W12||2010\u20132011||five speed automatic\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n|+Diesel engines\n!Model!!Years!!Types\n|-\n|3.0 V6 TDI||2010\u20132016||six speed automatic\n|}\n\n==Powertrain==\n{{As of|2007}}, [[powertrain]] options for the Phaeton include the following [[internal combustion engine|engines]].<ref>All data: {{Cite book|title=Automobile Revue 2007 |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2007 |publisher=Espace Media Groupe |location=Bern |ISBN=978-3-905386-07-3 |pages=519\u2013520}}</ref> [[4motion]] permanent [[four-wheel drive]] is the only driveline system available, except for the 2003 and 2004 model years when front wheel drive was available with the 3.2 litre engine.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n|+Petrol engines\n!Model!!Years!!Engine codes!!Engine type!!Power, torque at rpm!!0\u2013{{convert|100|km/h|0|abbr=on}} (s)!!Top speed\n|-\n|3.2 VR6||2002\u20132008||AYT / BKL / BRK||{{convert|3189|cc|abbr=on}} [[VR6 engine|VR6]]||{{convert|241|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,200, {{convert|315|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2,400 ||9.4||{{convert|239|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.6 VR6||2008\u20132016||?||{{convert|3597|cc|abbr=on}} VR6||{{convert|280|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,250, {{convert|370|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3,500 ||8.6||{{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}} (limited)\n|-\n|4.2 V8||2002\u20132016||BGH / BGJ / ?||{{convert|4172|cc|abbr=on}} V8||{{convert|335|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,500, {{convert|430|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3,500||6.9||{{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}} (limited)\n|-\n|6.0 W12 LWB (420PS)||2002\u20132004||BAN||{{convert|5998|cc|abbr=on}} [[W12 engine|W12]]||{{convert|420|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,000, {{convert|550|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3,000||6.1||{{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}} (limited)\n|-\n|6.0 W12 LWB (450PS)||2004\u20132011||BRN / BTT||{{convert|5998|cc|abbr=on}} W12||{{convert|450|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,050, {{convert|560|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2,750-5,200||5.9||{{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}} (limited)\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n|+Diesel engines\n!Model!!Years!!Engine codes!!Engine type!!Power, torque at rpm!!0\u2013{{convert|100|km/h|0|abbr=on}} (s)!!Top speed\n|-\n|3.0 V6 TDI (225PS)||2004\u20132006||BMK / CARA / CEXA||{{convert|2967|cc|abbr=on}} V6 turbo||{{convert|225|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 4,000, {{convert|450|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 1,400||8.8||{{convert|234|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.0 V6 TDI (233PS)||2007\u20132008||BMK / CARA / CEXA||{{convert|2967|cc|abbr=on}} V6 turbo||{{convert|233|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 4,000, {{convert|450|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 1,400||8.4||{{convert|234|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.0 V6 TDI (240PS)||2008\u20132016||BMK / CARA / CEXA||{{convert|2967|cc|abbr=on}} V6 turbo||{{convert|240|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 4,000, {{convert|500|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 1,500-3,500||8.3||{{convert|237|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|5.0 V10 TDI||2003\u20132007||AJS||{{convert|4921|cc|abbr=on}} V10 turbo||{{convert|313|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 3,750, {{convert|750|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2,000||6.9||{{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}} (limited)\n|}\n\nVehicles manufactured for sale in the North American market were only available with the 4.2 litre [[V8 engine|V8]] and 6.0 litre [[W12 engine]], both of which were electronically limited to {{convert|210|km/h|1|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe Phaeton features a [[Robert Bosch GmbH|Bosch]] ESP&nbsp;5.7 [[electronic stability control|Electronic Stability Programme]], with [[anti-lock braking system|Anti-Lock Braking System]] (ABS), [[Electronic brakeforce distribution|Electronic Brakeforce Distribution]] (EBD), Anti-Slip Regulation (ASR) [[traction control system]], [[Electronic Differential Lock]] (EDL), [[engine braking|Engine Braking Control]] (EBC), with emergency [[Brake Assist]] (BA).\n\nThe electronic differential lock (EDL) employed by Volkswagen is not, as the name suggests, a differential lock at all. Sensors monitor wheel speeds across an individual driven axle, and if one wheel is rotating substantially faster than the other (i.e. slipping) the EDL system momentarily brakes it. This effectively transfers power to the other wheel.\n\nVolkswagen was developing an electric version, but replaced it with their MEB2 platform for 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/motor-shows-geneva-motor-show/tesla-model-s-forces-radical-rethink-next-volkswagen-phaeton|title=Tesla Model S forces radical rethink for next Volkswagen Phaeton - Autocar|author=|date=|website=www.autocar.co.uk|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Volkswagen Phideon]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Volkswagen}}\n{{Volkswagen (Europe) timeline 1980 to date}}\n{{Volkswagen (North America) timeline 1980 to date}}\n\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2002]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:Volkswagen vehicles|Phaeton]]\n[[Category:All-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Flagship vehicles]]\n[[Category:Full-size vehicles]]\n[[Category:Luxury vehicles]]\n[[Category:Limousines]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by VR engines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Volkswagen Phaeton\n| image = 2005 VW Phaeton.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Volkswagen]]\n| production = 2002\u20132016\n| model_years = {{Plainlist|\n*2003-2016\n*2004-2006 (North America)\n}}\n| assembly = [[Dresden]], Germany\n| class = [[Full-size car|Full-size]] [[luxury car]] ([[F-segment|F]])\n| body_style = 4-door [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| platform = [[Volkswagen Group D platform#D1s|Volkswagen Group D1]]\n| related = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Audi A8]]\n*[[Bentley Continental GT]]\n*[[Bentley Continental Flying Spur (2005)|Bentley Continental Flying Spur]]\n}}\n| layout = [[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|F4 layout]] ([[4motion]])\n| engine = ''[[Petrol engine]]s:''<br/>3.2&nbsp;L [[List of Volkswagen Group petrol engines#3.2 VR6 24v (EA390)|''EA390 AYT / BKL / BRK'']] [[VR6 engine|VR6]]<br/>3.6&nbsp;L [[List of Volkswagen Group petrol engines#3.6 VR6 24v FSI (EA390)|''EA390'']] VR6<br/>4.2&nbsp;L [[List of Volkswagen Group petrol engines#4.2 V8 40v|BGH, BGJ]] [[V8 engine|V8]]<br>6.0&nbsp;L [[Volkswagen W12 engine|W12]] 2004\u20132011<br>''[[Diesel engine]]s:''<br>3.0&nbsp;L [[List of Volkswagen Group diesel engines#3.0 V6 24v TDI CR 150\u2013195 kW|TDI Common Rail (BMK / CARA / CEXA)]] V6 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]]<br>5.0&nbsp;L [[List of Volkswagen Group diesel engines#4.9/5.0 V10 TDI PD 230-258kW|AJS]] [[V10 engine|V10]] TDI 2003\u20132007\n| transmission = {{Plainlist|\n*5-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]] with [[tiptronic]]\n*6-speed automatic\n}}\n| wheelbase = {{Plainlist|\n*SWB: {{convert|2881|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n*LWB: {{convert|3001|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n}}\n| length = {{ubl |2002-2009: |SWB: {{convert|5055|mm|1|abbr=on}} |LWB: {{convert|5175|mm|1|abbr=on}} |2010\u20132016: |SWB: {{convert|5059|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} |LWB: {{convert|5179|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}}}\n| width = {{convert|1903|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1450|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|2184|-|2449|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n| successor = [[Volkswagen Phideon]] (China)\n}}\n\n[[File:Volkswagen W12.jpg|thumb|[[Volkswagen W12 engine|Volkswagen Group W12]] as fitted in the Phaeton W12]]\n[[File:VW_Concept_D_(IAA_1999)_1.jpg|thumb|left|Volkswagen Concept D at IAA 1999 in Frankfurt]]\n\nThe '''Volkswagen Phaeton''' ({{Audio|GT VW-Phaeton.ogg|listen}}) {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|e\u026a|t|\u0259n}} {{respell|FAY|t\u0259n}} (''Typ'' 3D) is a [[full-size car|Full-size]] ([[F-segment]] in Europe) [[luxury car|luxury]] [[sedan (automobile)|sedan/saloon]] manufactured by the German automobile manufacturer [[Volkswagen]], described by Volkswagen as their \"premium class\" vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volkswagen-sachsen.de |title=Volkswagen Sachsen GmbH |publisher=Volkswagen-sachsen.de |date= |accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Glaesernemanufaktur Dresden |url=http://www.glaesernemanufaktur.de/gmd.jsp?dok=&lang=en&docid=&ap= |title=GlaeserneManufaktur.de |publisher=GlaeserneManufaktur.de |accessdate=2010-10-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405044618/http://www.glaesernemanufaktur.de/gmd.jsp?dok=&lang=en&docid=&ap= |archive-date=2010-04-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Introduced at the [[Geneva Motor Show#2002|2002 Geneva Motor Show]], the Phaeton was marketed worldwide. Sales in North America ended in 2006 and global sales ended in 2016.\n\nThe name Phaeton derives from [[Phaethon|Pha\u00ebton]], the son of [[Phoebus]] (or [[Helios]]) in [[Greek mythology]], by way of the [[Phaeton body|phaeton auto body style]] and the [[Phaeton (carriage)|type of horse-drawn carriage]] that preceded it.\n\nProduction ended in March 2016 and an all-electric second generation was slated to be produced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-12-16/volkswagen-to-stop-making-top-end-phaeton-sedan-by-late-march |title=Volkswagen to Stop Making Top-End Phaeton Sedan in March |last=Behrmann |first=Elisabeth |date=16 December 2015 |website=Bloomberg.com |access-date=16 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://autoweek.com/article/vw-diesel-scandal/vw-suspend-phaeton-anticipation-diesel-crisis-pressures|title = VW suspends Phaeton.|date = |accessdate = December 19, 2015|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Starting in April 2017, the ''Gl\u00e4serne Manufaktur'' Dresden assembles the [[VW e-Golf|e-Golf]] instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnn.de/Dresden/Lokales/Scharfer-Start-fuer-den-e-Golf-aus-Dresden |title=Scharfer Start f\u00fcr den e-Golf aus Dresden |accessdate=2017-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==First and Second Generation (2002\u20132006/2007-2008) (GP0/GP1)==\n[[File:04 Volkswagen Phaeton (6827577840).jpg|thumbnail|left|Pre-facelift Volkswagen Phaeton]]\n\n===Development===\nThe Phaeton was conceived by [[Ferdinand Pi\u00ebch]], then chairman of [[Volkswagen Group]].<ref name=topgear2003/> Pi\u00ebch wanted Volkswagen engineers to create a car that would surpass the German prestige market leaders, [[Mercedes-Benz]] and [[BMW]]. The decision to release the Phaeton was, in part, a response to Mercedes' decision to compete directly with Volkswagen in the European marketplace with the low cost [[Mercedes-Benz A-Class#W168|A-Class]].\n\nIt was also intended to support the Volkswagen brand image. Although the [[Volkswagen Group]] already has a direct competitor in the full sized luxury segment, the [[Audi A8]], the Phaeton was intended to be more of a comfort oriented limousine, like the [[Mercedes-Benz S-Class]] and [[Lexus LS]], while the Audi A8 and [[BMW 7 Series]] are more sport oriented.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/car/02q3/volkswagen_phaeton_4motion_w-12-first_drive_review |title=Volkswagen Phaeton 4MOTION W-12 |department= First Drive Review - Auto Reviews |work=Car and Driver |date= |accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/tests/comparison/living-large/page_6_-_living_large_page_6 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217101312/http://www.roadandtrack.com/tests/comparison/living-large/page_6_-_living_large_page_6 |archive-date=2011-02-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nInitial development of the Phaeton, given the internal project code VW611, began with Pi\u00ebch giving his engineers a list of ten parameters the car needed to fulfill. Most of these specifications were not made known to the public, but a number of them were told to automotive reporters.\n\nOne of them was that the Phaeton should be capable of being driven all day at {{convert|300|km/h|0|abbr=on}} with an exterior temperature of {{convert|50|\u00b0C|0}} whilst maintaining the interior temperature at {{convert|22|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=GoAutoMedia |url=http://www.goauto.com.au/mellor/mellor.nsf/story2/8F252B3F3D6B8266CA25770E00001AC5 |title=Volkswagen 2009 Phaeton - Beijing show: VW facelifts Phaeton \u2013 again |work=GoAuto |date=2010-04-23 |accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref> Pi\u00ebch requested this even though the Phaeton's top speed was electronically limited to {{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}}.<ref name=topgear2003>''Top Gear'' Series 2 Episode 10, July 20, 2003</ref> Another requirement was that the car should possess torsional rigidity of 37,000 [[newton metre|N\u00b7m]]/[[degree (angle)|degree]].\n\nAt the [[International Motor Show Germany#1999|1999 International Motor Show Germany]], Volkswagen presented the [[Volkswagen Concept D|Concept D]], which was essentially a [[hatchback]] prototype of the Phaeton, with very similar design, [[V10 TDI]] engine, air suspension and all wheel drive.\n\n===Overview===\nThe Phaeton's platform, the [[Volkswagen Group D platform#D1s|Volkswagen Group D1 platform]], was shared with the [[Bentley Continental GT]] and [[Bentley Continental Flying Spur (2005)|Bentley Continental Flying Spur]]. Certain systems, such as the [[automatic transmission]] and some [[internal combustion engine|engines]], are also shared with the [[Audi A8]].\n\nCompared to the Audi A8L 4.2 litre FSI quattro, the Phaeton is {{Convert|545|lb|0|abbr=on}} heavier but is still competitive with the lighter A8 in most driving tests, due to the Phaeton's increased engine power (335&nbsp;hp versus 330) and a shorter axle ratio (3.65:1 versus 3.32).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/comparisons/2004-volkswagen-phaeton-page-3|title=2004 Audi A8L vs. BMW 745i, Jaguar XJ8, M-B S430, VW Phaeton Comparison Tests - Page 3 |work= Car and Driver|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> However, the weight gives the Phaeton considerably worse acceleration and poorer fuel economy compared to the A8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/luxury/112_0409_luxury_sedan_comparison/viewall.html|title=2004 Audi A8L vs 2004 BMW 745i vs 2004 Jaguar XJ8 Vanden Plas vs 2004 Lexus LS 430 vs 2004 Mercedes-Benz S430 vs 2004 Volkswagen Phaeton V8 Comparison |date=3 September 2004|work=Motor Trend Magazine|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Phaeton had the longest [[wheelbase]] in the Volkswagen passenger car line.\n\n===Features===\nDevelopment of the vehicle led to over one hundred individual patents specific to the Phaeton.{{citation needed|date=March 2012}} Distinctive features include a draftless four zone climate system, and standard [[Torsen]] based [[4motion]] [[four-wheel drive]].\n\nFor high ride comfort, it introduced [[Adaptive Air Suspension]] with [[Continuous Damping Control]] (CDC)-(Skyhook suspension). The same suspension system, with firmer settings, was introduced in the technically similar [[Audi A8#D3|Audi A8]] in November 2002.\n\nFirst Volkswagen with [[radar]] [[adaptive cruise control]]: [[automatic distance regulator]] (ADR).\n\n===Phaeton Lounge (2005)===\nThe Phaeton Lounge was a concept car based on a lengthened version of the Phaeton with seating for four (two pairs of seats facing each other) in the rear compartment. It features a W12 engine, a reinforced chassis, six speed [[Tiptronic]] automatic transmission, individual climate control for each passenger, front and rear wine coolers, a minibar, multi color mood lighting, a cigar humidor, two 17 inch monitors, DVD changer in the trunk, second DVD player in the rear cabin, and a Bluetooth enabled computer with a broadband connection.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2006/08/09/the-worlds-first-4wd-limo-is-a-volkswagen/ |title=The world's first 4WD limo is a Volkswagen |last=Nunez |first=Alex |website=Autoblog |access-date=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe vehicle was unveiled in 2005 Middle East International Motor Show.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2005/12/23/volkswagen-supersizes-the-phaeton/ |title=Volkswagen supersizes the Phaeton |last=Waterman |first=Stuart |website=Autoblog |access-date=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Production===\nThe Phaeton was hand assembled in an eco friendly factory with a glass exterior, the [[Transparent Factory]] ({{lang-de|Gl\u00e4serne Manufaktur}}) in [[Dresden]], Germany. This factory had a capacity of producing 20,000 vehicles a year, and was planned to expand to 35,000 vehicles a year.<ref name=failedexperiment>{{cite news|title=VW Phaeton: A few facts on a failed experiment|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20160404/OEM01/304049975/vw-phaeton:-a-few-facts-on-a-failed-experiment|accessdate=25 April 2016|work=Autonews|date=Apr 4, 2016}}</ref> It also assembled [[Bentley Continental Flying Spur (2005)|Bentley Continental Flying Spur]] vehicles destined for the European market until October 2006, when all assembly of the Bentley products was transferred to [[Crewe]], England.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nThe Phaeton body was fabricated and painted at the Volkswagen works at [[Zwickau]], Germany, and the completed bodies were transported approximately 100&nbsp;km by special road transport vehicles to the main factory. Most Phaeton engines, the W12 being the notable exception, were built at the VW/Porsche/Audi engine plant in [[Gy\u0151r]], Hungary.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n===Reception and sales===\n[[File:VW Phaeton 3.0 TDI 4Motion Tarantellaschwarz Interieur.JPG|thumb|Interior]]\n\nSales of the Phaeton fell far short of expectations. Its biggest market was China, followed by South Korea.<ref>{{cite web | last = Choi | first = Joseph | date = 30 July 2013 | url = http://www.nada.com/b2b/NADAOutlook/UsedCarTruckBlog/tabid/96/entryid/280/The-Volkswagen-Phaeton-to-Attempt-Successful-Rebirth-in-U-S-Market.aspx | title = The Volkswagen Phaeton to Attempt Successful Rebirth in U.S. Market | publisher = [[National Automobile Dealers Association]] | accessdate = 10 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the manufacturer stated the annual capacity of the new Phaeton plant at [[Dresden]] was 20,000; by September 2006 a four year total of 25,000 had been built,<ref>''skript manufaktura'' \u2013 Magazin der Gl\u00e4sernen Manufaktur Dresden, Nr.&nbsp;7, Herbst/Winter 2006, Seite 63</ref> with production running at approximately 6,000 cars annually. The domestic market was the Phaeton's strongest, with 19,314 Phaetons delivered in Germany alone by January 2009. Production decreased to 10,190 cars in 2012 and 5,812 in 2013.<ref>http://www.volkswagenag.com/content/vwcorp/content/de/homepage.bin.html/marginalparsys/textandimage_3/downloadFile/GB%2B2013_d.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703032256/http://www.volkswagenag.com/content/vwcorp/content/de/homepage.bin.html/marginalparsys/textandimage_3/downloadFile/GB%2B2013_d.pdf |date=2014-07-03 }} Gesch\u00e4ftsbericht 2013</ref> In Phaeton's production run that lasted 15 years, 84,253 units were built.<ref name=failedexperiment/>\n\nIn Canada, 93 Phaetons were sold in 2004, and in the first eight months of 2005, only 21 found owners. In the United States market, 1,433 Phaetons were sold in 2004, and 820 were sold in 2005, leading the company to announce that sales in the North American market would end after the 2006 model year. The [[Volkswagen W12 engine|W12 engine]]d models have depreciated significantly, and sell for a small fraction of their original cost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heise.de/autos/Clever-kaufen-und-Geld-sparen-Restwerte-bei-Gebrauchten--/artikel/s/2605/1\n|title=Gebrauchtschn\u00e4ppchen Phaeton|language=de}}</ref>\n\nThe Phaeton debuted at prices comparable to similar offerings from [[Mercedes-Benz]], [[BMW]], [[Lexus]] and the Volkswagen Group's own [[Audi A8]] (which shared its powertrain with the Phaeton). ''Motor Trend'' suggested that the \"VW badge on the hood may not say 'premium' to many auto shoppers\" but they were impressed at how the Phaeton drove.<ref>[http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/luxury/112_0409_luxury_sedan_comparison/viewall.html#ixzz1uPUeaFkx ]</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, Volkswagen reported the possibility of bringing the Phaeton back to the United States in the car's next product cycle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://noir.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109&sid=a.j7FDas6jw8&pos=12 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120715134415/http://noir.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109&sid=a.j7FDas6jw8&pos=12 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-15 |title=Volkswagen May Bring Back Scirocco, Phaeton to U.S. |date=2011-01-28 |publisher=bloomberg.com }}</ref> In Autumn 2013, ''[[The Economist]]'' placed Phaeton into the report on Europe's biggest loss making cars.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/graphicdetail/2013/09/daily-chart-18 |title=Daily Chart. Europe's biggest loss making cars |newspaper=The Economist | date=2013-09-25}}</ref> In October 2014, ''[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear Magazine]]'' placed the Phaeton on its list of \"The worst cars you can buy right now.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topgear.com/uk/photos/The-worst-cars-you-can-buy-right-now-2014-10-09 |title=The Worst Cars You Can Buy Right Now |publisher=[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear]] magazine |date=2014-10-09 |accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Volkswagen released the first update to the Phaeton. Subtle design changes were made by the introduction of chrome fog light covers and cherry red rear lights. The CD-based navigation system was upgraded to a DVD system, and the 3.0 V6 TDI engine had its power increased from 222 to 230bhp.\n\n==Third Generation (2008 Facelift) (GP2)==\nThe vehicle was unveiled in 2007 Geneva Motor Show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2007/03/07/geneva-motor-show-the-new-vw-phaeton/|title=Geneva Motor Show: The new VW Phaeton|author=Dan Roth|work=Autoblog|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nUpdate included new [[Light-emitting diode|LED]] [[daytime running light]]s, as well as a freshened centre console with revamped controls and materials. New [[gasoline direct injection|Fuel Stratified Injection]] (FSI) [[V6 engine|V6]] petrol engine with greater power and fuel efficiency (206&nbsp;kW / 280 PS) which satisfy [[European_emission_standards#Euro5|Euro-5]] emissions standards is also available.\n\nOther changes to the car for 2009 included: three new types of alloy wheels (17, 18 and 19&nbsp;inch), a slightly modified radiator [[grille]], three new exterior colours, the new leather colour, the new wood trims, white switch illumination instead of red, accent and switch trim in the new \"Warm gray\" colour, an upgraded car key, makeup mirror in the rear on the LWB version, dampers optimised for low-friction, [[reinforced carbon-carbon#Similar products|Carbon fibre-reinforced Silicon Carbide]] (C/SiC) [[ceramic composite]] brakes (front) on the Phaeton [[W12 engine|W12]], as well as a [[rearview camera]] ([[Rear Assist]]) and [[blind spot warning system]] [[Side Assist]].\n\n==Third Generation (2010 Facelift) (GP3)==\n[[File:2013 Volkswagen Phaeton V6 4MOTION TDi SWB Automatic 3.0.jpg|thumb|left|Volkswagen Phaeton (second facelift)]]\n[[File:VW Phaeton 3.0 V6 TDI 4MOTION (2. Facelift) \u2013 Heckansicht, 1. April 2012, Essen.jpg|thumb|right|Volkswagen Phaeton (second facelift)]]\nThe vehicle was unveiled in 2010 Beijing International Automotive Exhibition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vwmedia.com.cn/PageNews/NewsDetails_en.aspx?articleID=430|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116014043/http://vwmedia.com.cn/PageNews/NewsDetails_en.aspx?articleID=430|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 January 2013|title=Volkswagen Group Debuts Six Brands in China at Auto Beijing 2010|website=vwmedia.com.cn|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2010/04/23/beijing-2010-2011-volkswagen-phaeton-ups-the-luxe/ |title=Beijing 2010: 2011 Volkswagen Phaeton ups the luxe |last=Korzeniewski |first=Jeremy |website=Autoblog |access-date=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe car for 2011 got a new front fascia to more closely resemble the Volkswagen styling direction first seen on the Golf Mk VI. This included new LED running lights, bi-xenon headlights and a new bumper with LED fog lights. The rear [[LED]] clusters were altered to mimic those found on facelifted Touran, Sharan, the new Touareg and the new Passat.\n\nThe interior benefited from some new technologies, but retained the 2009 MY layout. The Phaeton was offered as a normal wheelbase and long wheelbase models, with five seat layout or an optional four seat interior. In the five seat version, the front seats can be adjusted 12 ways. Standard features include all wheel drive, air suspension, and four zone automatic climate control. A multifunction steering wheel can be ordered in leather or wood leather.\n\n===New technologies===\n*[[Automatic Distance Control]] adaptive cruise control with new Stop&Go function\n*[[Front Assist]] [[collision avoidance system]]\n*[[Dynamic Light Assist]] non-glare [[highbeam]] <ref name=\"volkswagen-media-services1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.volkswagen-media-services.com/medias_publish/ms/content/en/pressemitteilungen/2010/04/22/phaeton_debuts_with.standard.gid-oeffentlichkeit.html|title=Phaeton debuts with new design and new technologies|accessdate=22 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720152841/https://www.volkswagen-media-services.com/medias_publish/ms/content/en/pressemitteilungen/2010/04/22/phaeton_debuts_with.standard.gid-oeffentlichkeit.html|archive-date=20 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*[[Traffic sign recognition]] that can also detect [[overtaking restriction]]s<ref name=\"volkswagen-media-services1\"/>\n*GPS-Navigation with [[Google Earth]]\n*[[3G]] [[Mobile internet]] ([[UMTS]])\n\n===Transmissions===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n|+Petrol engines\n!Model!!Years!!Types\n|-\n|3.6 V6 FSI||2010\u20132015||six speed automatic\n|-\n|4.2 V8||2010\u20132016||six speed automatic\n|-\n|6.0 W12||2010\u20132011||five speed automatic\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n|+Diesel engines\n!Model!!Years!!Types\n|-\n|3.0 V6 TDI||2010\u20132016||six speed automatic\n|}\n\n==Powertrain==\n{{As of|2007}}, [[powertrain]] options for the Phaeton include the following [[internal combustion engine|engines]].<ref>All data: {{Cite book|title=Automobile Revue 2007 |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2007 |publisher=Espace Media Groupe |location=Bern |ISBN=978-3-905386-07-3 |pages=519\u2013520}}</ref> [[4motion]] permanent [[four-wheel drive]] is the only driveline system available, except for the 2003 and 2004 model years when front wheel drive was available with the 3.2 litre engine.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n|+Petrol engines\n!Model!!Years!!Engine codes!!Engine type!!Power, torque at rpm!!0\u2013{{convert|100|km/h|0|abbr=on}} (s)!!Top speed\n|-\n|3.2 VR6||2002\u20132008||AYT / BKL / BRK||{{convert|3189|cc|abbr=on}} [[VR6 engine|VR6]]||{{convert|241|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,200, {{convert|315|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2,400 ||9.4||{{convert|239|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.6 VR6||2008\u20132016||?||{{convert|3597|cc|abbr=on}} VR6||{{convert|280|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,250, {{convert|370|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3,500 ||8.6||{{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}} (limited)\n|-\n|4.2 V8||2002\u20132016||BGH / BGJ / ?||{{convert|4172|cc|abbr=on}} V8||{{convert|335|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,500, {{convert|430|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3,500||6.9||{{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}} (limited)\n|-\n|6.0 W12 LWB (420PS)||2002\u20132004||BAN||{{convert|5998|cc|abbr=on}} [[W12 engine|W12]]||{{convert|420|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,000, {{convert|550|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3,000||6.1||{{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}} (limited)\n|-\n|6.0 W12 LWB (450PS)||2004\u20132011||BRN / BTT||{{convert|5998|cc|abbr=on}} W12||{{convert|450|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,050, {{convert|560|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2,750-5,200||5.9||{{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}} (limited)\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n|+Diesel engines\n!Model!!Years!!Engine codes!!Engine type!!Power, torque at rpm!!0\u2013{{convert|100|km/h|0|abbr=on}} (s)!!Top speed\n|-\n|3.0 V6 TDI (225PS)||2004\u20132006||BMK / CARA / CEXA||{{convert|2967|cc|abbr=on}} V6 turbo||{{convert|225|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 4,000, {{convert|450|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 1,400||8.8||{{convert|234|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.0 V6 TDI (233PS)||2007\u20132008||BMK / CARA / CEXA||{{convert|2967|cc|abbr=on}} V6 turbo||{{convert|233|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 4,000, {{convert|450|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 1,400||8.4||{{convert|234|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.0 V6 TDI (240PS)||2008\u20132016||BMK / CARA / CEXA||{{convert|2967|cc|abbr=on}} V6 turbo||{{convert|240|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 4,000, {{convert|500|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 1,500-3,500||8.3||{{convert|237|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|5.0 V10 TDI||2003\u20132007||AJS||{{convert|4921|cc|abbr=on}} V10 turbo||{{convert|313|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 3,750, {{convert|750|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 2,000||6.9||{{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}} (limited)\n|}\n\nVehicles manufactured for sale in the North American market were only available with the 4.2 litre [[V8 engine|V8]] and 6.0 litre [[W12 engine]], both of which were electronically limited to {{convert|210|km/h|1|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe Phaeton features a [[Robert Bosch GmbH|Bosch]] ESP&nbsp;5.7 [[electronic stability control|Electronic Stability Programme]], with [[anti-lock braking system|Anti-Lock Braking System]] (ABS), [[Electronic brakeforce distribution|Electronic Brakeforce Distribution]] (EBD), Anti-Slip Regulation (ASR) [[traction control system]], [[Electronic Differential Lock]] (EDL), [[engine braking|Engine Braking Control]] (EBC), with emergency [[Brake Assist]] (BA).\n\nThe electronic differential lock (EDL) employed by Volkswagen is not, as the name suggests, a differential lock at all. Sensors monitor wheel speeds across an individual driven axle, and if one wheel is rotating substantially faster than the other (i.e. slipping) the EDL system momentarily brakes it. This effectively transfers power to the other wheel.\n\nVolkswagen was developing an electric version, but replaced it with their MEB2 platform for 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/motor-shows-geneva-motor-show/tesla-model-s-forces-radical-rethink-next-volkswagen-phaeton|title=Tesla Model S forces radical rethink for next Volkswagen Phaeton - Autocar|author=|date=|website=www.autocar.co.uk|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Volkswagen Phideon]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Volkswagen}}\n{{Volkswagen (Europe) timeline 1980 to date}}\n{{Volkswagen (North America) timeline 1980 to date}}\n\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2002]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:Volkswagen vehicles|Phaeton]]\n[[Category:All-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Flagship vehicles]]\n[[Category:Full-size vehicles]]\n[[Category:Luxury vehicles]]\n[[Category:Limousines]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by VR engines]]\n", "name_user": "Rawja", "label": "safe", "comment": "\"was\" produced, no longer \"is\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volkswagen_Phaeton"}
